We put out a call to our readers to be part of the panel of tasters.They came together on a Saturday morning and were presented with hot cross buns from five leading supermarkets - with no branding - on separate plates. The buns were served warm without butter to enable a truer test in terms of texture, fruit, spice and freshness.Auditor Jade Craig was on hand to monitor the objectivity of the blind-tasting process, from removing the packaging to numbering the products, overseeing the preparation and adding up the score sheets. Judges' comments: These buns scored high on appearance, with a shiny glaze and consistent crosses. The panel liked the soft, light texture and good amount of fruit and spices.Price: R14.99Judges' comments: The buns were not glazed but tasters liked their golden-brown colour. They looked and tasted fresh, but some tasters found them a little on the dry side.Price: R21.99 Which supermarket makes SA's most delicious Peppermint Crisp tart? Judges' comments: Appearance was good although most tasters felt the buns lacked spice.Price: R15.99 Judges' comments: Despite their attractive appearance, these buns were deemed "not very fresh".Price: R14.99 Judges' comments: The buns were described as doughy and as having little or no spice. There was no glaze and most said the amount of fruit was stingy.Price: R17.99